Installation and Setu
-------------------------------
$ sudo apt-get update-----Updates the list of available packages and versions from repositories.
Always run this before installing new software to ensure you're getting the latest version.

$ sudo apt install docker.io----Installs Docker 

$ docker version-----Shows the installed Docker version.

$ sudo systemctl status docker----Displays the current status of the Docker service (active, inactive)

$ sudo systemctl enable docker-----Enables Docker to start automatically on system boot.

$ sudo systemctl start docker------Starts the Docker service manually if it’s not running.

Working with Docker Images and Containers
---------------------------------------------
$ sudo chown $USER /var/run/docker.sock----Gives the current user ownership of the Docker socket so you can run docker commands without sudo.
  
$ docker images-----Lists all Docker images available locally on your machine.
  
$ docker pull httpd----Downloads the official Apache HTTP server (httpd) image from Docker Hub.

$ docker network ls-----Lists all Docker networks used for container communication.

$ docker inspect httpd------Shows low-level configuration details of the httpd image (JSON format).

Running and Accessing Containers
---------------------------------
$ docker run -itd httpd-------Runs a new httpd container:
here:
-i: interactive mode
-t: allocates a pseudo-TTY(terminal)
-d: detached mode 

$ docker run -itd -p 82:80 httpd
Runs the container and maps host port 82 to container port 80 .
-p 82:80 → This is the port mapping.
82: Port on your host machine (outside the container).
80: Port inside the container (used by Apache HTTP Server).
Why use this?
Apache in the container listens on port 80, but if you mapped it directly (like -p 80:80), you'd need root privileges and might conflict with other services.
So, using a different host port like 82 allows safe access.

$ docker ps------Lists all running Docker containers.

$ docker exec -it <id> /bin/bash----Executes an interactive Bash shell inside the running container with the specified <id>.

$ cd htdocs/----Navigates into the htdocs directory.


